{
  "texts": [
    "We use the subscript Q and the conditioning on the quantum state E to mark the distinction with the classical version ∆(Z, U m |E).For a discussion on why this is the correct measure against quantum adversaries, see [19] 'Section 2'.We can now define what deterministic, seeded and two-source extractors are at the function level.",
    "For simplicity of notation, we omit the conditioning on the side information E (or E), for example, writing H ∞ (X) instead of H ∞ (X|E).",
    "Definition 5 (Deterministic randomness extractor).",
    "A (ϵ, n, m)-deterministic extractor is a functionExt d: {0, 1} n → {0, 1} m (7)that maps a random bit string X ∈ {0, 1} n with some specific propertiesfoot_7, to a new variable Z = Ext d (X) that is (optionally quantum-proof) ϵ-perfectly random, see Definition 3 (optionally Definition 4).Definition 6 (Two-source randomness extractor).",
    "Given two independent random variablesX ∈ {0, 1} n 1 and Y ∈ {0, 1} n 2, with min-entropy H ∞ (X) ≥ k 1 and H ∞ (Y) ≥ k 2 respectively, a (n 1, k 1, n 2, k 2, m, ϵ)-two-source randomness extractor is a function Ext 2: {0, 1} n 1 × {0, 1} n 2 → {0, 1} m (8)where Ext 2 (X, Y) is ϵ-perfectly random, see Definition 3 (optionally Definition 4).We discuss the role of side information for two-source extractors in Section 3.2."
  ]
}